        "tree_location": "front yard",
        "reason_removal": "Dying tree",
        "tree_description": "Very large white oak with fungus. Reason for Removal:Dying treeComments:Microscopic examination of the submitted sample revealed the oak bracket fungus, Pseudoinonotus dryadeus. This\ndecay fungus is found near the base of oak and true fir trees. This fungus is closely related to and was previously\nclassified within Inonotus, many of which can cause extensive decay of the trunk, root flare, and buttress\nroots.?This is a white rot which may reduce structural integrity by degrading lignin and/or cellulose. This fungus\nmay grow alone or in clusters and is generally present between summer and fall. The fruiting bodies of this fungus\nhave an amorphous shape, a light yellow/buff color of the surface, and golden droplets along the surface.",
